The Class of 1969 presented a dedication plaque in honor of the late school administrator and teacher -Dale Cockrell.

Pictured is Bill Beaty presenting the plaque to alumni association President- Tracy Roark Smith.

The plaque will be later presented to Cheyenne School Administration to be placed at the school for viewing.

Thank you Class of 1969 for presenting this honor.

post_text:
The Alumni Association would like to thank again Bill Beaty (class of 69) for writing a song for the event titled ‘Thinkn Bout Home’, which he sang with his daughter, Carey Beaty- Drake.

We would like to share those lyrics. Thank you again Bill and Carey for sharing your talents.

Please Like and Share

Thinkin Bout Home

Chorus 1
Thinkin bout home
And those good ole high school days
Thinkin bout life
I thank God for how I’s raised
Saturday nights
(Playin pool)and draggin Main
(a picture show)—last chorus
The world goes crazy so I’m
Thinkin bout home

V1
Found a box of my old pictures
That I somehow left behind
And my senior high school Yearbook dated 1969
Stored way back in the attic…

The 2019 alumni banquet invitations have been mailed. Thanks goes out to the alumni who have returned your reservations.

If you are an alum and did not receive an invitation and would like to attend the banquet, please message our Facebook page your contact information and we will mail you an invite.

You can also review and use the following attached invitation and mail your reservation and dues to:

CHS-SC ALUMNI ASSOCIATION
PO BOX 213
CHEYENNE, OK. 73628

We look forward to seeing everyone at the banquet on April 20th.

Look for updates on alumni weekend on our Facebook page and in The Cheyenne Star.

Thank you for your support

Cheyenne Educational Foundation
February 27, 2019 at 10:42 PM ·

Are you proud to be a Cheyenne Bear? Are you proud to be a Cheyenne graduate? Check out the Cheyenne-Strong City Alumni Association Facebook page and send them your current address to receive an invite to the annual alumni banquet. Aren't you curious to see what your former classmates are doing now?

The Cheyenne Educational Foundation knows Cheyenne graduates are special! We are proud to help them with scholarships and all our special projects.
This has only been possible thanks to our generous donors-like the 50 year reunion classes who have challenged later classes to match or beat their donations.
With age and experience come wisdom-so we are curious-what advice would you alums have for the Seniors of 2019 or even for anyone who graduated after you?
Share your advice here!

post_text:
This next Saturday, March 31st, is the Cheyenne-Strong City Alumni Banquet in the CHS student lounge.

Doors open at 5p and the banquet starts at 6p. Tomorrow, March 26th is the deadline to make your reservation. See our Facebook timeline for details.

This years Alumni President, host and master of ceremonies will be Bill Beaty -Class of 1969.

Here is a great - but funny photo memory of Bill and Marilyn Rook.

We look forward to having you at the banquet for fun, food, entertainment and a time to share great memories from our high school days at CHS and Strong City.

Share your photo memories on our Facebook timeline.

In honor of the passing of Manuel Hensley..... In 2013 the Strong City Baptist Church celebrated its 100th year of existence. On that occasion Manuel was recognized at the oldest male member of the congregation. At that service I sat behind Shirley Orgain Johnson and her family. Across the church was Reverend Aubrey who though scheduled to speak was too weak to do so. Brother Aubrey passed shortly after. Last year Shirley passed and this week Manuel. I am posting the following video of Ralph Chapman, DOM, singing 'Celebrate me Home' ......

Even if you don't want to play, we encourage you to attend and watch our alumni play in this fun competition between even and odd graduating years.

We look forward to seeing everyone on Saturday.

The Alumni Association will reserve tables at the banquet for the following class reunions: 1951, 52, 57, 60, 61, 62, 63, 67, 68, 77, 82, 83, 84, 88, 89, 90, and 2007.

Cheyenne Old Settlers Reunion
April 11, 2017 at 11:02 AM ·

CHEYENNE-ARAPAHO OLD SETTLERS REUNION CARAVAN
On April 13th, 2017, the Cheyenne-Arapaho Old Settlers Caravan will be meeting at 8:00 a.m. in Cheyenne at the courthouse. We will caravan around town then proceed to Elk City. We will meet other members of the caravan in Elk City at the United Grocery Store parking lot on the east side of the store. The caravan will then travel from Elk City to Cordell, to Clinton, to Arapaho, to Hammon and return to Cheyenne. There will be a lunch stop in Clinton. If you are interested in participating please contact Karla Gwartney by April 12, 2017, at (580) 821-6223. We hope to have as many people as possible go on this fun filled adventure.

The Cheyenne-Strong City Alumni Association would like to congratulate 2014 CHS graduate Callie Maddux for being chosen as this years 2017 Cheyenne-Arapaho Old Settler's Queen.

Click on the link below for details

https://www.facebook.com/cheyenneoldsettlers/posts/1875400196050964:0
shared_text:
Cheyenne Old Settlers Reunion
February 23, 2017 at 8:47 AM ·

The Cheyenne and Arapaho Old Settlers Committee is pleased to announce that Callie Maddux has been chosen as the 2017 C&A Old Settler's Queen. Callie is the daughter of Jim and Jana Maddux, and the granddaughter of James Albert and Linda Maddux and Paula Isch, all of Cheyenne and Earnest and Rose Isch. Callie's great great-grandfather Samuel F. Maddux made the Oklahoma land run on April 19, 1892 and homesteaded just north of Cheyenne. Her parents, aunts and uncles still live on this land. Her great great great grandparents John Henry and Martha Emma Wilson Anderson also made the run along with three great great great uncles. Three of her relatives, Archie Anderson Brewer (1922), Lanita Maddux Carroll(1957) and Jamie Maddux Allen(1982)), have served as Cheyenne Arapaho Old Settlers Queens. Her grandmother, parents and aunt have all served for many years as active members of the Old Settler's committee. Callie will be crowned during the Cheyenne and Arapaho Old Settler's parade on April 22nd, 2017.

shared_text:
Cheyenne Old Settlers Reunion
July 26, 2016 at 2:26 PM ·

A little history of the origins of The Cheyenne-Arapaho Old Settler's reunion -Part 1

On April 19, 1892 the Cheyenne-Arapaho Land Run began at noon with the firing of a Cavalry man's gun. By nightfall there were 50 people who called the town of Cheyenne their home. They had arrived on horseback, covered wagon and even on foot. On April 19, 1907 "Daddy" Hez Cox, a Cheyenne businessman who had participated in the run, called a meeting to establish an association to preserve the early day history of western Oklahoma. The Old Settler's Association established the custom of annually commemorating the date of the C & A Land Run with a celebration. The first "Old Settler's Reunion" was a picnic with a basket dinner, square dance and a horse race.

Watch for Part 2 soon.......

(Information provided by Judy and Dale Tracy)

post_text:
Do you remember the Cheyenne and Strong City school songs?

For those of you attending the banquet on Saturday, below is the lyrics for you to learn and sing at the banquet. Just to keep in mind, we are looking for a song leader. Who will it be?

Joyous and Ever Loyal

Joyous and Ever Loyal,
Let us boost Cheyenne High,
Let every heart sing,
Let every voice ring,
There’s no time to grieve or sigh,
It’s ever onward,
Our course pursuing
May defeat, ne’er our ador cool,
But united we will boost for her,
Our Own High School.

Strong City School Song

Stand Up and Cheer,
Cheer loud and long for old Strong City,
For today we raise the white and blue,
Above all others,
A sturdy hand now is playing,
We are sure to win this game,
We’re here to win,
We’ve got to win,
For it’s Strong City High School Day

Just some pics of students at CHS back in 1988 and 89. Enjoy!!

If you did not receive an invitation to the Alumni Banquet or haven't confirmed your reservation, contact Wanda Purcell at 580-445-6061.

We look forward to seeing all of you there supporting our CHS students and the Cheyenne-Strong City Alumni Association.

Thank You
